<DOC><DOCNO> AP880810-0079 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 0825EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Seals     08-10 0168</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Britain-Seals,0172</SECOND><HEAD>Scientists Meet In London To Discuss Seal Deaths</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Scientists from European countries bordering theNorth and Baltic seas today began a two-day meeting to discuss thedeaths of thousands of seals along their coasts, the environmentalgroup Greenpeace said.   Greenpeace, which is sponsoring the meeting with the Universityof London, said the scientists will assess the extent of thedeaths, the cause and any possible action which may be taken.   ``While governments argue over who is to blame for the currentcrises in the North and Baltic seas, the common seal in this areafaces extinction,'' said Greenpeace spokesman Andrew Booth.   The 12 scientists attending the meeting come from Britain,Denmark, the Netherlands, Germany, Norway and Sweden, saidGreenpeace press spokeswomen Sue Adams.   A virus is suspected as the cause of the seals' deaths. WestGerman environmentalists have blamed the virus on waste fromindustry, but scientists say they do not really know its exactcause. The deaths began early this year.</TEXT></DOC>